observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

Require the refund of cash advances that have not been used for a period two months; 

Require all AOs to promptly liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period. Otherwise, consider imposing administrative sanctions for unjustified delays in liquidation; 

Conduct a review of unliquidated cash advances before approving new cash advance requests for AOs with outstanding balances to prevent overlapping advances; 

Issue a demand letter to the former Municipal Accountant at his last known address to facilitate the settlement of unliquidated cash advances; 

Regularly follow up with concerned government agencies to ascertain the current addresses or assignments of individuals who were granted cash advances while previously assigned in the LGU and send appropriate demand letters for immediate liquidation of their outstanding cash advances; 

Cause the withholding of salaries of AOs who are still employed with the agency until they have fully settled their unliquidated cash advances; 

Record the proposed adjusting journal entries to reflect the accurate balances of the affected accounts in the financial statements as at year-end; and 

Record the utilization of cash advances only upon submission of complete and valid documents, ensuring accurate and transparent accounting practices.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

Record the procurement of welfare goods, drugs and medicines, as well as medical, dental and laboratory supplies and semi-expendable properties to proper asset accounts following the perpetual inventory method; 

Adopt the moving average method for costing inventories; and 

Record the necessary reclassifying journal entries for the noted accounting errors for proper presentation of the accounts in the financial statements; 

Require the Supply Officer to:

Coordinate regularly with the LDRRMO and MHO for the maintenance of the stock cards for each inventory item in their custody and to attach distribution list/s to the RIS; 

Conduct periodic physical inventory of supplies every semester and prepare and submit RPCI to the Audit Team; 

Issue ICS to support the issuance of various semi-expendable properties totaling ₱1,483,848.00 and submit the same to the Audit Team; 

Provide the necessary details in the previously issued ICS and succeeding issuance thereof, particularly, the serial numbers, brand, model and useful life of semi-expendable properties issued; 

Prepare and maintain the required forms, registries and reports for semi-expendable properties and assign a separate ICS control number for low-valued items and high-valued items to strengthen the controls and safeguards over the semi-expendable properties; 

Conduct annual physical count of semi-expendable properties and to prepare the RPCSP; 

Require the former employees to return the properties previously issued to them; 

Ensure that all outgoing officials/employees or retired LGU employees return or surrender the government properties issued to them; 

Discontinue the issuance of properties to Job Order workers; 

Direct the Municipal Accountant and Supply Officer to maintain complete Supply Ledger Card and Stock Cards, respectively, for each item of supplies and materials or inventory account and conduct regular reconciliation of their inventory records.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Observe proper accounting of semi-expendable properties using the prescribed new accounts;
Record the necessary reclassifying journal entries for proper presentation of expense accounts in the financial statements for the issuance of semi-expendable properties amounting to ₱1,125,179.00;
Make the necessary retrospective adjustments in the books for the reclassification of PPE items aggregating ₱17,875,346.55   that fall below the capitalization threshold as identified in the provided schedule of the Audit Team; and
Review the lapsing schedule and determine the details of properties worth ₱1,578,296.46 that were lumped into one item for proper reclassification of PPE items that fall below the ₱50,000.00 threshold;
Require the Supply Officer to:
Issue ICS for the issuance of semi-expendable properties totaling ₱385,625.00 and furnish copies thereof to the Audit Team;
Provide the useful life of semi-expendable properties issued in the ICS; and
Prepare and maintain the required forms, registries and reports for semi-expendable properties and assign separate ICS control numbers for low-valued items and high-valued items to strengthen the controls and safeguards over the semi-expendable properties;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to:
Maintain complete Semi-Expendable Property Ledger Card and Semi-Expendable Property Card, respectively, for each item of semi-expendable properties; and
Formulate a policy/memorandum determining the estimated useful life of semi-expendable properties, and provide a copy thereof to the Audit Team.
Create an Inventory Committee to conduct annual physical count of semi-expendable properties still in the custody of the Supply Officer and prepare the RPCSP to verify their existence and condition.

We recommended that Management initiate the compliance with the guidelines and procedures for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE account balances by establishing an Inventory Committee to oversee and conduct the process.
We also recommended that Management:
Direct the existing Inventory Committee to strictly conduct the required physical count of all PPE at least once a year using the proper format and submit the RPCPPE to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of each year;
Require the Property Custodian to:
Maintain Property Cards for all PPE of the Municipality; and
Review and update PARs every three years or upon transfer of accountability;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer – Designate to determine the estimated useful lives of the properties with no recorded depreciation using historical data from similar assets and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant as reference in the computation of depreciation costs;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Update all Property Ledger Cards and reconcile records with the Property Custodian;
Provide depreciation costs for the identified completed projects totaling ₱133,029,921.05 for fair presentation of the PPE accounts in the financial statements;
Obtain missing details such as the nature, date of acquisition and economic useful lives of completed projects, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer – Designate, to provide the depreciation costs of the remaining PPE accounts totaling ₱129,340,560.48; and
Make the necessary adjustments in the books to correct the accounting errors on the misclassification of some PPE items and non-derecognition of items already distributed to end-users to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Establish a special account and maintain the corresponding subsidiary ledgers under the General Fund for the recording of receipts and utilization of the 70 percent share of environmental fees; and
Prepare the necessary entries upon transfer of funds from the Trust Fund to the General Fund and ensure that all subsequent receipts of environmental fees are correctly recorded as income and proper accounting of related expenses or assets charged thereto are taken-up in the books;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to:
Request a resolution from the Sangguniang Bayan authorizing the establishment and maintenance of a separate bank account specifically designated for the 70 percent share of environmental fees to prevent misapplication or misuse of funds;
Maintain a separate cashbook to record the collections and deposits of these funds; and
Ensure that all collections are directly deposited in the designated bank account for proper monitoring and control;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Accountant, to transfer the funds upon opening of a separate bank account for proper segregation of funds;
Instruct the Municipal Tourism Officer to:
Stop incurring expenditures against these funds until an appropriation ordinance is enacted, ensuring proper authorization for disbursement and utilization; and
Develop an investment plan specifying the PPAs to be funded by the special account, duly approved by the Municipal Tourism Council, for inclusion in the AIP for proper allocation and utilization of funds;
Direct the Local Finance Committee to:
Recommend the passage of a supplemental appropriation ordinance to allocate the available funds for the identified PPAs of the Municipal Tourism Council; and
Stop treating these funds as trust funds but classify them as “special funds under the General Fund” observing proper authorization through the enactment of an appropriation ordinance.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the MDRRMO to:
Ensure that the PPAs funded by the LDRRMF are strictly aligned with disaster risk reduction and management activities, preventing misallocation of funds;
Stop charging administrative expenses to the LDRRMF to ensure proper fund utilization; and
Include the list of PPAs to be charged against the unexpended balances of LDRRMF of previous years in the annual LDRRMFIP for inclusion in the AIP, subject to the recommendation of the LDRRMC and approval of the local sanggunian, ensuring the optimal use of available resources;
Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure proper charges to the LDRRMF;
Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to allocate funds for MOOE of the LDRRMO under the General Fund of the Municipality to prevent the use of the LDRRMF for PPAs not directly related to disaster risk reduction and management activities; and
Instruct the MDRRMO and Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to prioritize the implementation of PPAs under Continuing Appropriations at the beginning of the year.  In cases where projects are discontinued, funds shall be re-appropriated to more critical and relevant PPAs for disaster prevention, mitigation and preparedness.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to:
Require the contractors of the two completed infrastructure projects to submit valid financial instruments equivalent to the retention money totaling ₱249,891.17 with a validity period of one year from the date of issuance of the Certificates of Completion;
Deduct the 10 percent retention money equivalent to 50 percent of the value of works amounting to ₱2,499,539.56 from the next progress billing for the Construction of Public Market (Phase 1);
Subject initial progress payments exceeding 50 percent of the works and one-time payments for 100 percent completion to retention money equivalent to at least 10 percent of the 50 percent of the value of the completed work for projects that are satisfactorily undertaken and on schedule; otherwise, impose additional retention money on the remaining progress payments equivalent to 10 percent;
Require the contractors to submit a valid financial instrument equivalent to the retention money in case they request its substitution which will only be accepted if the project is on schedule and satisfactorily undertaken;
Release the retention money to contractors upon final acceptance of the project; and
Verify all claims for payment of infrastructure projects and ensure that these are duly supported with complete and proper documentation before certifying and endorsing them for payment;
Direct the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer – Designate, to:
Submit the lacking documents; and
Ensure that the Certificates of Completion include the “conforme” portion of the contractors, the pictures of the implemented projects are properly labeled and dated, and Statements of Work Accomplished are prepared by the contractors.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the BAC and the Municipal Engineer – Designate to:
Ensure compliance with the necessary conditions and criteria required to qualify for undertaking infrastructure projects by administration;
Strictly observe the regulations governing the procurement and implementation of infrastructure projects by administration; and
Execute formal contract agreements with the laborers, in accordance with the pakyaw system, if the Municipality opts for this method of engagement;
Require the Municipal Engineer – Designate to reconcile the noted inconsistencies in the issued Certificates of Completion and DTRs of laborers;
Direct the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer – Designate, to:
Submit the lacking documents; and
Ensure that the pictures of the implemented projects are properly labeled and dated; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to verify all claims and ensure that these are duly supported with complete and proper documentation before certifying and endorsing them for payment.

We recommended that Management:
Require the MSWDO, in coordination with the Sangguniang Bayan, to formulate its own implementing guidelines on the grant of medical assistance and other financial assistance to constituents which should clearly define eligibility criteria, prescribed rates, frequency of availment, necessary documentary requirements and approving authorities to ensure consistency and compliance with government regulations;
Direct the MSWDO to strictly adhere to the internal policies to be established for the grant of medical assistance and other financial assistance;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the MSWDO, to:
Submit the lacking documents to substantiate each claim; and
Ensure that all financial assistance disbursements are properly supported with appropriate and complete documentation;
Cause the refund of the educational assistance amounting to ₱4,000.00; and
Utilize the trust funds received for their intended purpose.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the SB Secretary to regularly furnish the Municipal Accountant with copies of the minutes of meetings at the end of each month to serve as a reference for computing any overpayment of RATA to SB members;
Direct the HRMO to:
Submit the necessary certifications to the Municipal Accountant duly supported with approved DTRs at the end of each month as bases for determining any overpayment of RATA to the department heads;
Take necessary steps to reconcile discrepancies in the DTRs and leave cards of municipal department heads, ensuring that all erroneous or unrecorded leave entries are corrected;
Conduct a monthly reconciliation of approved DTRs with employees’ leave cards to promptly identify and address any incorrect entries; and
Accurately record all leaves taken by employees in their respective leave cards to maintain reliable and consistent records;
Require the Municipal Accountant to:
Adhere strictly to the prescribed computation of RATA for SB members and municipal officials based on their actual attendance during regular sessions or verified work performance within a month. In case of any overpayment of RATA, it shall be deducted from the RATA payrolls for the succeeding month; and
Ensure that claims for RATA are supported with complete documentation before processing their payments; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, to cause the refund of the overpayment of RATA from the concerned SB members and municipal officials in the total amount of ₱632,600.00.
We further recommended that Management instruct all employees, including the department heads, to properly accomplish their DTRs to ensure completeness and accuracy of information provided therein.

We recommended that Management:
Formulate and adopt policy guidelines on the grant of in-kind donations duly approved by the Sangguniang Bayan to establish clear criteria for entitlement and documentary requirements for each type of assistance to ensure regularity of transactions and proper utilization of government funds.  Otherwise, each donation should be individually approved through a resolution from the SB, explicitly authorizing its grant;
Stop granting donations, contributions, grants and gifts that fall outside the mandate of the Municipality;
Stop granting financial or in-kind assistance to non-stock, non-profit corporations/foundations, private corporations and religious groups/organizations;
Stop granting financial or in-kind assistance to national government officials for requests that are personal in nature, as these do not fall within the authorized expenditures of the Municipality;
Stop granting financial assistance to DepEd personnel for transportation expenses related to seminars and conferences, particularly if such will be charged to the General Fund, as these expenses should be covered by the DepEd’s own budget or the SEF, when applicable;
Stop granting financial assistance to national government officials stationed in the Municipality, beyond the honoraria or allowances specifically authorized by law;
Stop the practice of reimbursement in the procurement of goods and services;
Require all department heads to include in their PPMPs all goods and services needed by their office or planned PPAs and submit the same to the Municipal Budget Officer and BAC Secretariat for consolidation into APP;
Designate specific personnel to document the distribution of goods to intended recipients which includes taking of pictures as evidence that goods procured by the Municipality were actually delivered and received by beneficiaries;
Stop the practice of printing the names of municipal officials on donated properties.  Instead, use the official seal or the name of the Municipality to properly indicate government ownership and funding; and
Cause the refund of the following expenditures:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Submit immediately the lacking documents identified per transaction for in-kind donations to determine the purpose/objective of the requested assistance, the parties requesting for such assistance as well as the nature and quantity of the goods being requested, and to support the distribution of the donated goods/materials;
Re-submit properly accomplished distribution lists, addressing the lacking details in the initially submitted lists, indicating therein the quantity and particular items received by each recipient duly certified by the municipal personnel who issued or distributed the goods for further evaluation;
Require the proper accomplishment of distribution lists by the implementing offices with complete details as to the name of recipients, type of goods and quantity received duly signed by recipients and certified by the issuing municipal personnel, and the same shall be supported with pictures during the conduct of the distribution;
Verify that all goods transferred to the barangays are properly recorded to ensure proper monitoring and accountability and submit copies of the JEVs related to said transactions to the Audit Team for review;
Reconcile the identified inconsistencies/discrepancies in the supporting documents for the donated medicines, monoblock chairs and foldable tables and cause refund of the unaccounted units, if warranted;
Exercise due diligence in verifying the completeness and correctness of supporting documents before certifying DVs for payments; and
Refrain from processing any claims for in-kind donations that are not fully substantiated with complete and proper supporting documents.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Property Custodian to:
• Strictly comply with the required physical count of all properties at least once a year using the proper format and to submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of each year;
• Maintain Property Cards for all PPE of the LGU;
• Provide inventory tags/sticker on all properties of the LGU to facilitate a methodological system of inventory-taking and to strengthen internal control on PPE;
• Review all the PARs of all properties of the LGU and cause the renewal thereof when necessary, especially those that were issued three years ago;
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to
• Update all Property Ledger Cards and have these reconciled with the records of the GSO;
• Continue tracing the transactions recorded under the Land account and reconcile with the records submitted by the GSO and Municipal Assessor;
• Prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries to provide depreciation costs for the PPE accounts totaling ₱205,728,233.28 upon receipt of the estimated useful lives from the Municipal Engineer, otherwise use the useful lives provided under DPWH Department Order No. 176 series of 2015 and COA Circular No. 2003-007;
• Make the necessary reclassifying journal entries for the noted accounting errors to reflect the collect balances of the affected accounts in the financial statements;
• Review the lapsing schedule, identify all items with no specific quantity and details and were lumped into one item, and ensure to depreciate them separately; and
• Provide retrospective adjustment to all items recorded under PPE account but fall below the ₱50,000.00 threshold;
c. Instruct the GSO, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, to secure the documents required under the DENR AO No. 2016-21 to facilitate the titling of the land; and
d. Instruct the Municipal Engineer to determine the estimated useful lives of the properties with no depreciation cost based on the experience of the agency with similar assets, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant.

We recommended that Management:
a. Re-assess the hiring of consultants and determine their capabilities based on proven expertise, experience and capability;
b. Instruct the Bids and Awards Committee Chairman to adhere with the principles on transparency and competitiveness by conducting public bidding or other alternative modes of procurement, if warranted, in the procurement of consultancy services;
c. Require the Municipal Accountant to refrain from using government funds to pay the services of the private lawyer if his functions are not purely technical in nature; and
d. Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking supporting documents for further review and evaluation.

a. Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, taking into account the allocation of the cost incurred for consolidated road projects to each road network comprising thereof based on the Program of Works;
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the recorded road networks in the books of accounts with the inventory of local roads and road maps;
c. Require the Supply Officer to prepare a Report of Local Road Network at the end of each accounting period;
d. Instruct the Head of the Inventory Committee to conduct annual inventory of road networks using the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network System; and
e. Upon reconciliation of records, require the Municipal Accountant to adjust the balance of road networks in the books of accounts, if necessary, and maintain subsidiary ledger for roads and road components for every road network.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the BAC to ensure that the RFQs are fully and properly accomplished to indicate all the necessary information such as the document date and control number;
b. Instruct the BAC to require the bidders to indicate all information vital in the evaluation of the quotations such as the brand offered, price validity period and warranty;
c. Instruct the BAC to always prepare a resolution recommending the award of the contract to the Single or Lowest Calculated and Responsive Quotation in all procurements conducted through alternative methods; and
d. Instruct the BAC Secretariat to ensure that the required PhilGEPS posting of procurement opportunities in the agency, and the Notice of Award, Notice to Proceed and contract be strictly observed.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the SWMO-Designate to propose in a meeting of all officials and sectors concerned the strategies to gradually implement a policy on waste segregation at source and at barangay level;
b. Instruct the SWMO-Designate to include in its proposed PPAs the provision for perimeter barrier or topographic constraints to enclose the whole area to avoid unauthorized access;
c. Require the personnel assigned in the disposal facility to maintain basic records to monitor daily waste collection, transfer, processing, disposal, site entries, and special occurrences such as fire, accidents, spills unauthorized loads and daily waste inspection logs; and
d. Instruct the SWMO-Designate, in coordination with other officials, to identify and formulate policies and Sangguniang Bayan Resolutions that will help the LGU in achieving its goals in solid waste management which may include a comprehensive waste segregation and collection system in the barangays, private establishments and other areas of the LGU, imposition of fees for its implementation, and charging of fines and penalties against persons committing the prohibited acts as provided in Section 48 of RA No. 9003.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Agriculturist and GSO to submit a report on the physical count of breeding stocks;
b. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to trace in the accounting records all purchases of breeding stocks and record the same in the WOABSLC;
c. Require the Municipal Agriculturist to prepare a comprehensive analysis of all issuances and movements of breeding stocks including the death or loss of animals, receipts of agricultural produce and changes in the fair market value resulting from price and physical changes;
d. Require the Municipal Agriculturist to conduct further investigation on the circumstances surrounding the deaths and transfers/unauthorized replacement of the animals and initiate proper action against the beneficiaries in accordance with the terms and conditions stipulated in the Animal Dispersal Contract;
e. Upon determining all the price and quantity changes or movements in breeding stocks, require the Municipal Agriculturist to submit the reports and supporting documents to the Municipal Accountant and Supply Officer;
f. Require the Municipal Accountant to update the columns in WOABSLC pertaining to births of offspring and stock dispositions;
g. Require the Municipal Accountant to draw necessary journal entries to adjust the balance of Breeding Stocks in the books of accounts. Likewise, provide the necessary adjusting journal entry to record the four calves and three goats purchased in November 2018 including the changes in fair market value; and
h. Require the General Services Officer to prepare the WOABSPC using the information provided by the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Agriculturist.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Accountant to review the transactions recorded under the CIP account and prepare CIPLC for each project that are still recorded under the account;
b. Instruct the Municipal Engineer to verify the status of the infrastructure projects implemented by administration relative to the construction materials that are still recorded under CIP account and provide the accomplishment and inspection reports to the Municipal Accountant and Audit Team for proper disposition;
c. Require the Municipal Engineer to conduct regular monitoring of infrastructure projects of the LGU, and prepare and submit a periodic status report of the same to the Municipal Accountant for proper recording and classification of projects in the books of accounts;
d. Instruct the Municipal Health Officer to provide an update to the DOH regarding the Communal Comfort Room Building and the completion of the additional civil works requirement to facilitate the release of the remaining project fund; and
e. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary journal entries to adjust the misstatements noted in the recording of CIP related transactions including the provision of depreciation costs for the completed projects.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the GSO to instruct all accountable officers or end-users of government vehicles or equipment to prepare Request for Pre-Repair Inspection indicating the property to be repaired with its property number, and the identified defects;
b. Require the Inspection Committee to prepare Pre-Repair Inspection Report based on the evaluation made;
c. Direct the GSO to properly accomplish the Waste Material Report;
d. Upon completion of repairs or replacements made, instruct the GSO to request for Post-Repair Inspection from the Inspection Committee;
e. Require the Inspection Committee to prepare Post-Repair Inspection Report and forward the same to the GSO;
f. Require the GSO to issue a Certificate of Acceptance indicating clearly that the works or service done are in conformity with the specifications of the contract;
g. Require the GSO to maintain a record of repairs for all properties of the LGU which shall form part of the supporting documents of disbursements for repair and maintenance; and
h. Instruct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to ensure that the cost of the completed repair and maintenance services are paid directly to the suppliers and not through reimbursements so as to withhold the applicable taxes.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the BAC to ensure that all procurements of the LGU follow the rules and regulations under RA No. 9184 and its IRR including the procurement of web hosting services and annual renewal thereof;
b. Instruct the Human Resource Management Officer to review the financial capability of the LGU and the plantilla positions to create an IT-related position that will handle the administration of the website and other IT related functions in the LGU, otherwise, delegate the web administration functions to one or more personnel with basic knowledge of computer and web technology;
c. Direct Shareable, Inc. to complete the training of the selected web administrators as stipulated in the contract;
d. Direct the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the BAC, to ensure that payments to be made for web hosting services are based on contracts completed after the conduct of appropriate procurement procedures;
e. Instruct the Tourism Officer, as the one currently in charge with the administration of the website, to formally make a communication request to DICT Region 1, to avail the web hosting services of the government or the GWHS;
f. Require Shareable, Inc. to submit documents and proof of the updates made in the website to justify the increase of payments made in CY 2022, and proof that malware removal and maintenance were not part of their original deliverables, otherwise, require the refund thereof; and
g. Instruct the web administrators to fully observe all existing laws, rules and regulations requiring posting of pertinent reports and documents in government official websites.

We recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:
a. Require the collectors concerned to produce immediately the missing cash tickets;
b. Direct the collectors to fully accomplish the RCDs including the RCDs Report/Control Number and the portion for the Accountability for Accountable Forms;
c. Strictly review the RCDs in a daily manner including the counting of the balance of accountable forms declared by the collectors and signing of the Verification and Acknowledgment portion thereof; and
d. Require all collectors to prepare monthly their individual RAAFs which shall be the basis for the preparation of the monthly their consolidated RAAF and ensure to submit the same.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Supply Officer to strictly comply with the required physical count of all properties at least once a year using the proper format and to submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;
b. Require the Supply Officer to provide inventory tags/sticker on all properties of the LGU to facilitate a methodological system of inventory-taking and to strengthen internal control on PPE;
c. Require the Supply Officer to maintain Property Cards for all PPE of the LGU;
d. Require the Municipal Accountant to update all Property Ledger Cards and have these reconciled with the records of the Supply Officer;
e. Instruct the Supply Officer to review all the PARs of all properties of the LGU and cause the renewal thereof when necessary especially those that were issued three years ago;
f. Require the Municipal Accountant to continue tracing the transactions recorded under the Land account and to reconcile with the records submitted by the Supply Officer and Municipal Assessor;
g. Instruct the Supply Officer, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, to secure the documents required under the DENR AO No. 2016-21 to facilitate the titling of the land;
h. Instruct the Municipal Engineer to determine the estimated useful lives of the properties with no depreciation cost based on the experience of the agency with similar assets, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant; and
i. Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary journal entries to provide depreciation costs for the PPE accounts totaling ₱173,591,195.08.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Accountant to review the transactions recorded under CIP account and prepare CIPLC for each project that are still recorded under the account;
b. Instruct the Municipal Engineer to verify the status of the infrastructure projects implemented by administration relative to the construction materials that are still recorded under CIP and provide the accomplishment and inspection reports to the Municipal Accountant and Audit Team for proper disposition;
c. Instruct the Municipal Engineer to prepare the program of works and other related studies for the additional works required by the DOH in the Communal Comfort Building;
d. Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to include in budget preparation the fund required to complete the Communal Comfort Building;
e. Require the Municipal Accountant to transfer the total contract amount of ₱960,000.00 relative to the Construction of Communal Comfort Building to Other Structures account and recognize the balance of ₱80,000.00 as Accounts Payable; and
f. Upon reconciliation and determination of all completed projects that are still recorded under CIP, instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary journal entries to adjust the CIP, Government Equity, and other appropriate asset accounts; and the provision of depreciation costs for the completed projects.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and Supply Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, taking also into account the allocation of the cost incurred for consolidated road projects to each road network comprising thereof based on the Program of Works;
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the recorded road networks in the books of accounts with the inventory of local roads and road maps;
c. Require the Supply Officer to prepare a Report of Local Road Network at the end of each accounting period;
d. Create an inventory committee or group that will primarily handle the inventory of local road network system;
e. Instruct the Head of the Inventory Committee to conduct annual inventory of road networks using the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network System; and
f. Upon reconciliation of records, require the Municipal Accountant to adjust the balance of road networks in the books of accounts and maintain subsidiary ledger for roads and road components for every road network.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Secretariat to properly and completely prepare the bidding documents in accordance with the requirements of each procurement activity leaving no blank spaces, options and notes/instructions;
b. Require the BAC to require the winning bidders to fully accomplish and update the Special Conditions of the Contracts, and submit the same, as revised, to the Audit Team;
c. Instruct the BAC to prepare and approve the Abstract of Bids as Calculated right after the evaluation of bids;
d. Instruct the BAC-TWG to observe strictly the guidelines in the conduct and preparation of Post-Qualification Reports to establish properly the eligibility of the participating bidders;
e. Require the BAC Chairman to ensure that the contractor will submit the CSHP approved by DOLE before approving or entering into contract; and
f. Require the BAC, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer to immediately submit the lacking documents to the audit team for further verification, technical evaluation and inspection.

We recommended that Management:
a. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to trace in the accounting records all purchases of breeding stocks and record the same in the WOABSLC;
b. Require the Municipal Agriculturist to prepare a comprehensive analysis of all issuances and movements of breeding stocks including the death or loss of animals, receipts of agricultural produce and changes in the fair market value resulting from price and physical changes;
c. Require the Municipal Agriculturist to conduct further investigation on the circumstances surrounding the deaths and unauthorized transfers or replacement of the animals and initiate proper action against the beneficiaries in accordance with the terms and conditions stipulated in the Animal Dispersal Contract;
