2.11. We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, taking also into account the allocation of the cost incurred for consolidated road projects to each road network comprising thereof based on the Program of Works;
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the recorded road networks in the books of accounts with the inventory of local roads and road maps;
c. Require the Supply Officer to prepare a Report of Local Road Network at the end of each accounting period;
d. Create an inventory committee or group that will primarily handle the inventory of local road network system;
e. Instruct the Head of the Inventory Committee to conduct annual inventory of road networks using the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network System; and
f. Upon reconciliation of records, require the Municipal Accountant to adjust the balance of road networks in the books of accounts, if necessary, and maintain subsidiary ledger for roads and road components for every road network.

3.22. We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Accountant to review the transactions recorded under CIP account and prepare CIPLC for each project that are still recorded under the account;
b. Instruct the Municipal Engineer to verify the status of the infrastructure projects implemented by administration relative to the construction materials that are still recorded under CIP and provide the accomplishment and inspection reports to the Municipal Accountant and Audit Team for proper disposition;
c. Require the Municipal Engineer to conduct regular monitoring of infrastructure projects of the LGU, and prepare and submit a periodic status report of the same to the Municipal Accountant for proper recording and classification of projects in the books of accounts; and
d. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary journal entries to adjust the misstatements noted in the recording of CIP related transactions including the provision of depreciation costs for the completed projects.

4.16. We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Accountant to adjust the final budget amounts of the current year’s appropriation which was understated by ₱3,624,810.40;
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to present only budget amounts for CO under continuing appropriations and ensure that the amount presented in the SCBAA are corroborated with the existing records by using the formula for computation for proper check and balance;
c. Require the Municipal Accountant in coordination with the Municipal Budget Officer to properly account the continuing appropriations by providing a list of unimplemented capital outlays and balances; and
d. Require the Municipal Budget Officer to revert the balances of MOOE available for appropriations and balances of completed CO.

5.16. We recommended that Management:
a. Instruct the Supply Officer to propose for an adequate and secured stockroom;
b. Require the Supply Officer to consolidate the Requisition Issue Slip issued weekly and prepare Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued which shall serve as the basis of the Municipal Accountant in recording the issued supplies as expense;
c. Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to maintain complete Supply Ledger Cards and Stock Cards, respectively, for each item of supplies and materials or inventory account;
d. Require the Supply Officer to coordinate regularly with the LDRRMO and MHO for the maintenance of the stock cards for each inventory item in their custody and to attach distribution list/list of recipients to the RIS;
e. Instruct the Supply Officer/Inventory Committee to conduct periodic physical inventory of supplies semestrally and to prepare and submit Report on Physical Count of Inventories to the Audit Team;
f. Require the Supply Officer to issue Inventory Custodian Slips to inventories/supplies considered as small tangible items with estimated service life of more than one year to establish accountability over them; and
g. Instruct the Supply Officer to secure the RIS or any equivalent proof that the inventory items that were non-moving for more than six years were already issued or consumed, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant for proper adjustment in the books

9.6. We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Treasurer to make series of follow-ups with the NGAs whose checks for the refund of unexpended fund transfers became stale on their end through email and other modes of communication to ensure immediate feedback;
b. Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to send written communications to the source agencies confirming any remaining balances of unliquidated or unexpended fund transfers;
c. Require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the offices concerned, to prepare the liquidation reports pertaining to the unliquidated fund transfers;
d. Require the Municipal Treasurer to return the unexpended balance of fund transfer to the source agencies or Bureau of Treasury, as applicable; and;
e. For fund transfers that could not be traced in the records or from the source agencies, instruct the Municipal Accountant to request for write-off in accordance with the procedures and requirements provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We reiterated the previous year’s audit recommendations that Management:
a. Instruct the Supply Officer to secure the RIS or any equivalent proof that the items were already issued or consumed, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant for proper adjustment in the books;
b. Provide a stockroom or space for the use of Supply Office to keep the supplies and materials to be purchased including equipment which are to be issued to the requisitioning head of department needing the same;
c. Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain Supplies Ledger Card for each specific type of Inventory;
d. Require the Supply Officer to record purchases and issuances of supplies through the use of the prescribed Stock Card for each type of inventory;
e. Instruct the Supply Officer to consolidate weekly the RIS using the RSMI and submit the original copies thereof to the Municipal Accountant;
f. Require the Municipal Accountant to record the inventories using the perpetual inventory system and weighted average cost method, and ensure that the relative expense will be recognized only upon the receipt of RSMI from the Supply Officer; and
g. Instruct the Supply Officer to conduct a periodic physical count of its inventories and report the same in the prescribed RPCI and cause its submission to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Treasurer to send written notices to the NGAs whose checks for the refund of unexpended fund transfers became stale on their end to return the said checks for the replacement;
b. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to make the following suggested journal entry to adjust the checks which became stale while validating the refunds made to the source agencies: Cash in Bank Ᵽ 35,648.00 / Due to NGAs Ᵽ 35,648.00;
c. Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to send written communications to the source agencies confirming any remaining balances of unliquidated or unexpended fund transfers;
d. Require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and Municipal Engineer, to prepare the liquidation reports pertaining to the unliquidated fund transfer;
e. Require the Municipal Treasurer to return the unexpended balance of fund transfer to the source agencies or Bureau of Treasury, as applicable; and
f. For fund transfers that could not be traced in the records or from the source agencies, instruct the Municipal Accountant to request for write-off in accordance with the procedures and requirements provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require all department heads and the BAC to judiciously prepare and accomplish all the documents needed in the conduct of procurement including the PR and PO;
b. Instruct the BAC Chairman and Municipal Accountant to thoroughly review and evaluate the PR and PO documents before procurement;
c. Require the BAC to update the form used in gathering the lowest calculated and responsive quotation for all procurement activities involving procurements through alternative methods to indicate the ABC, and other terms and conditions of the contract;
d. Direct the BAC Chairman to sign the RFQs as a formal letter from the agency;
e. Instruct the BAC to require the suppliers to indicate the brand of goods they are offering and other necessary information that may affect the final evaluation of the offers;
f. Require the BAC Secretariat to prepare Abstract of Quotations after receiving and evaluating the price quotations received by the BAC;
g. Require the BAC to prepare BAC Resolutions Recommending to the HoPE the Award of Contract in favor of the supplier with the Lowest Calculated and Responsive Quotation; and
h. Require the BAC and Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking Mayor’s Permit of the suppliers for CY 2020 and other required documents to facilitate further review of the said transactions.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the BAC to submit all PPMPs for CY 2020 encompassing all the procurement activities of the LGU including infrastructure projects, goods and services other than the commonly-used office supplies and equipment;
b. Instruct all department heads to properly and fully accomplish their PPMPs in order to facilitate consolidation;
c. Require the BAC to consolidate the PPMPs into Indicative and Final APP in accordance with the guidelines provided under Section 7 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and GPPB Circular No. 07-2015; and
d. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the disbursements of the LGU are duly supported with approved procurement plan.

We recommended that Management:
a. Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to refrain from collecting price quotation fees for procurements conducted through alternative methods that are outside the scope of Section 4.4, Appendix 8 of the 2016 IRR of RA No. 9184;
b. Instruct the members of the BAC, BAC Secretariat and Technical Working Group to request for the payment of their honoraria in the year the competitive biddings are conducted to avoid the use of prior years’ unutilized proceeds from the sale of bidding documents;
c. Require the Municipal Treasurer to transfer the unutilized proceeds from the sale of bidding documents to the General Fund; and
d. Require the Municipal Budget Officer to consider the amount balances as part of the local funds of the LGU in the budgeting process.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents to support the distribution of the donated goods/materials and to determine the purpose/objective of the recipients;
b. Require the barangay officials concerned to submit reports on the utilization of the supplies and materials received from the Municipality such as, but not limited to Resolutions of the Sangguniang Barangay, Program of Work, pictures before, during and after work completion, Inspection Report, Property Acknowledgement Receipt and/or Inventory Custodian Slip, as applicable;
c. Instruct the members of the SB to stop from directly approving and processing any request from constituents, barangays or other organizations for assistance in the form of cash or goods which is beyond their power provided under RA No. 7160;
d. Require the BAC to ensure that all goods intended to be donated are procured in accordance with the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 to avoid advance deliveries or purchases without perfected contract or purchase order;
e. Require the Municipal Accountant to secure the original copies of Certificates of Appearance, boarding pass, travel orders and Itinerary of Travel from the personnel of the RTC to avoid double payment of expenditures; and
f. Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to ensure that PPAs or items of appropriations in the annual budget are specifically identified and not expressed in generic terms; otherwise, secure authority from the SB before implementing any project.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the drivers to properly accomplish the trip tickets indicating all the necessary information for the control and monitoring of fuel consumption, and instruct them to ensure that passengers will sign thereon;
b. Direct the Supply Officer to use the RIV form or its equivalent in all fuel requisition and issuance transactions;
c. Require the Supply Officer to instruct the gasoline station to indicate in the individual invoices, the plate number of the vehicle requesting fuel;
d. Instruct the Supply Officer to prepare Daily Gas Issue Record, Summary of Requisition and Issue Voucher, Monthly Report of Official Travels and Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption; and
e. For vehicles and heavy equipment with defective fuel gauge, require the Supply Officer to undertake immediately the repair thereof, and shall ensure to hold the drivers responsible for not reporting defective fuel gauge.

We recommended that the Management:
a. Require the HRMO-Designate to formulate internal rules and procedures on Overtime Services in line with the general policies and guidelines set forth in CSC and DBM Joint Circular No. 2, s.2004 and Joint Circular No. 1, s.2015 and for review and approval of the Local Chief Executive;
b. Require all Department Heads to approve only those overtime services which could not be rendered by the municipal employees on regular workdays, and ensure that the Authority to Render Overtime and Accomplishment Report contain the specific works to be done with quantity and time allocation;
c. Require the Municipal Accountant to verify the payrolls on Overtime Pay whether the two-hour minimum overtime services on workdays and the one-hour breaks for breakfast, lunch, or supper and rest, and every three hours of continuous overtime service are strictly observed; and
d. Require all Department Heads to prioritize the availing of Compensatory Time-Off instead of paying Overtime Pay which could be used by the LGU for other purposes.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the SWMO-Designate to expedite the preparation of the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan of the LGU in accordance with RA No. 9003;
b. Require the SWMO-Designate to assess other disposal facilities to fully stop the operations of the existing dumpsite while waiting for DENR-EMB’s final resolution on the sanitary landfill proposal of the LGU;
c. Require the Municipal Engineer to prepare the technical plans for the provision of sufficient security fencing around the said dumpsite to prevent illegal entries and trespassing;
d. Require the personnel assigned in waste collection and dumpsite to maintain basic records to monitor daily waste collection, transfer, disposal and special occurrences such as fire, accidents, spills unauthorized loads and daily waste inspection logs; and
e. Instruct the SWMO-Designate, in coordination with other officials, to identify and enforce possible policies that will help the LGU in achieving its goals in solid waste management which may include a comprehensive waste segregation and collection system in the barangays, private establishments and other areas of the LGU, imposition of fees for its implementation, and charging of fines and penalties against persons committing the prohibited acts as provided in Section 48 of RA No. 9003.

We recommended to Management the following courses of action:
Require the Supply Officer, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, to prepare and maintain an Inventory of all Local Roads and a Road Map. Likewise, the preparation of Report of Local Road Network and Physical Count of Local Road Network must be observed yearly;
Create an inventory committee or group that will primarily handle the inventory of local road network system;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare adjusting journal entries to recognize changes upon completion of the required inventory reports and reconciliation with the Registry of Public Infrastructures; and
Require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, to prepare a schedule of estimated useful lives of public infrastructure and submit the same to the Audit Team in order to provide depreciation for assets under public infrastructure accounts.

We recommended that Management:
Require all municipal officials and employees concerned to liquidate their cash advances on time, otherwise, impose administrative sanctions against them for any unjustifiable reasons on their failure to liquidate cash advances within the prescribed period, in accordance with Section 89 of PD 1445, COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 and Civil Service Commission No. 0676 dated June 17, 2004;
Cause or order the withholding of any money claims against the municipal officials and employees concerned until they have fully settled their unliquidated cash advances;
Strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 and COA Circular No. 96-004 in the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances relative to travels and trainings; and
Determine and exhaust all possible remedies for the liquidation of dormant unliquidated cash advances; otherwise, request for write-off thereof in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended the Management the following courses of actions:
Instruct all concerned employees and officials to strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 96-004, Executive Order No. 298 and COA Circular No. 2012-003 relative to expenses on travel, seminars and conferences;
Require all signatories of the documents, particularly on Itinerary of Travel, Liquidation Reports and Disbursement Vouchers to certify only travel-related expenses which are in observance with the said provisions;
Obtain plane tickets directly from airline companies to avoid other charges imposed by travel agencies; however, booking with these agencies may be allowed provided that their offers will be scrutinized through comparison of existing prices on airline websites, and request itineraries with detailed breakdown of cost and/or have their quotations submitted in order for the management to choose the most advantageous price; and
Require the employees or officials concerned to provide justification for the reimbursement of educational tour expenses which are deemed unnecessary; otherwise, cause the refund of the said claims.

We recommended the Management to:
Limit the procurement of goods and services on a reimbursement basis, unless the circumstances warrant its application;
Secure at least three (3) price quotations from known and eligible suppliers if reimbursement could not be avoided in order to comply with the competitive aspect of the procurement law;
Require all department heads to carefully determine/consider all the goods and services needed for the year for inclusion in the Annual Procurement Plan in order to minimize the need for reimbursement; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to deduct the corresponding withholding taxes in all disbursements required by the BIR including those made on reimbursement basis.

We recommended Management to:
Require the BAC to use only Shopping as alternative mode of procurement, if warranted, based on the conditions set forth under Section 52 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184;
Require the BAC Secretariat to consolidate the Municipality’s PPMPs and to stop the practice of procuring supplies and materials by piecemeal through shopping;
If office supplies and equipment are not available in the DBM-PS, secure certification therefor before resorting to other modes of procurement; and
Observe strictly the guidelines and documentary requirements prescribed in Appendix A, Annex H of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 in using alternative modes of procurement.

